# Git Workflow

Never commit straight to `main`. Every change lands on its own branch so a bad
change can be reverted by dropping one branch/merge instead of untangling
`main`.

## Branch naming

- `feature/<short-name>` — major features or multi-part work
  (e.g. `feature/strategy-forge`).
- `bug/<short-name>` — minor fixes, small tweaks, single-issue changes
  (e.g. `bug/mobile-footer`).
- `chore/<short-name>` — housekeeping that isn't a feature or a fix
  (docs, rules, config) (e.g. `chore/git-workflow-rule`).

## Flow

1. Branch from an up-to-date `main`:
   `git checkout main && git pull origin main && git checkout -b <type>/<name>`
2. Commit focused changes on the branch.
3. Push the branch: `git push -u origin <type>/<name>`.
4. Merge into `main` with a merge commit (keeps the branch as a revert point):
   `git checkout main && git merge --no-ff <type>/<name>`
5. Push `main`: `git push origin main`.

## Rules

- **Ask before committing.** Only commit/merge when the user explicitly asks.
- **One concern per branch** — don't mix an unrelated fix into a feature branch.
- Keep merged branches around for now (don't delete) so we retain easy
  revert points unless the user says otherwise.
- Never force-push `main`.
